dataIdInfo.idAbs: Pour points derived from NHDPlus V2.1 flow direction rasters and the NHDPlus V2.1 WBD HU12 snapshot. Three sets of pour points are provided: From and to points that identify the location where raster flow leaves the HU12 polygon, and a third "vector pour point" selected "upstream" for use in detecting flow confluences near the raster pour point locations. This dataset is PROVISIONAL and SUBJECT TO REVISION.
dataIdInfo.idPurp: These pour points provide locations where one HU12 flows into another as defined by the NHDPlus flow direction rasters. This information may be useful for various applications that require to know the location of these raster flow "pour points".

dataIdInfo.suppInfo: WBD Pour Point Processing Steps 1. The input flow direction raster is clipped to the HU12 polygon extent 2. A weight grid is created where cells inside the HU12 polygon are set to one and cells outside the HU12 are set to zero 3. Flow accumulation is calculated for the current extent, using the weight grid 4. The cell with maximum flow accumulation is selected. A point feature is created at the center of this grid cell, and its flow direction and flow accumulation value (number of cells it drains) is recorded. (This value will saved in the FDCODE field). The flow accumulation value is divided by the number of cells in the HUC12 to populate the PCTPOUR field. 5. The flow direction at this location is recorded. Flow direction codes are as follows if the cell is not a sink (ie if that cell flows out of the HU12): > 32 64 128 > 16 0 1 > 8 4 2 If the FDCODE value is zero, the location is a sink (does not flow to another HUC12 polygon area. The ISSINK field will be set to one. 6. If the pour point is a sink, and elevation data is provided, it is clipped to the HUC12, filled, and steps 1 to 5 above are rerun using the new flow directions. If this "fill and spill" is done, the output FILL field will be set to one. Otherwise, FILL will be zero. 7. The cell with the largest flow accumulation value more than a specified number of cells (default 4) from the pour point is determined. This is the "vector pour point", its location and flow accumulation value (number of cells) is captured and divided by the number of cells in the HU12 and saved in the VPCTPOUR field. 8. If the flow direction is defined as a power of two, a second point location is generated using the flow direction downstream (to-point) 9. A point in polygon overlay is done to dermine the HUC12 polygon under this to-point location. The HUC12 code is copied to the DOWNHUC field. 10. the HUC12 code and to-huc code (HUC_12, HUC_12_DS, or HU12, ToHUC, depending on WBD version used) is saved to the output table. 11. DOWNFLAG is populated using the following codes: DOWNFLAG = 0 the ToHUC discovered using the flow directions matches the ToHUC found in WBD for that HU12 polygon. DOWNFLAG = 1 ToHUC is null. This is common when for pour points that flow out of the WBD polygon feature class, for example, for the pour point flowing out of the fdr/fac raster processing units (processing tiles). DOWNFLAG = 2 the ToHUC discovered using the flow directions does NOT match ToHUC found in WBD for that HU12 polygon. This can be caused by incorrect ToHUCs or inconsistencies between DEM-generated flow and flow designated in the WBD. 12. ToHUC_Dist is caculated if DOWNFLAG = 2. This value can be used as a diagnostic tool to determine the cause of the problem.

attr.attrdef: Percentage of HU12 upstream of pour point. If this value is near 100.0, it is very likely that the raster flow directions align closely with the WBD HU12 boundary.
Flag indicating whether HU12 fill processing was done
Flow Direction code, indicating pour point flow direction. These are defined as powers of two, with 1 being east, 2, southeast, etc. to 128 being northeast.

Distance (in meters) from from pour point to the WBD ToHUC - this value is calculated only if the DOWNHUC is not equal to the ToHUC. If this value is small, it is likely that there is misaligment or other confusion between the raster flow directions and the WBD designated flow.
0: ToHUC and DOWNHUC match 1: ToHUC and DOWNHUC do not match 2: DOWNHUC is null
The pour point is a sink. Raster flow does not leave the HU12.
